{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15444"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.17,0.43,0.05,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49111"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3346"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10834"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20880"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E is a bacterium commonly found in the human stomach. The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for 2005 was awarded jointly to two Australians - Barry J. Marshall and J. Robin Warren - for the work they did in identifying \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E and it role in the pathogenesis of peptic ulcer disease. Their discovery of \u003Cem\u003EH pylori \u003C/em\u003Ein 1984 revolutionised the understanding of gastric pathophysiology and established  clearer associations with gastric cancer, atrophic gastritis and peptic ulcer disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of Helicobacter pylori?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonises the small intestine","It is a gram-positive spiral bacterium","Has adhesins as virulence factors","Lacks urease enzyme production","Requires alkaline environment for growth"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E is a \u003Cstrong\u003Egram-negative spiral bacterium\u003C/strong\u003E that colonises the gastric mucosa. It produces urease, which allows it to survive in the acidic environment of the stomach. The bacterium does not \u003Cstrong\u003Elack urease enzyme production\u003C/strong\u003E; rather, urease is a key enzyme that helps it neutralise stomach acid. \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E does not \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonise the small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E; it is primarily found in the stomach. One of its virulence factors includes \u003Cstrong\u003Eadhesins\u003C/strong\u003E, which help it adhere to the gastric epithelium. It does not \u003Cstrong\u003Erequire an alkaline environment for growth\u003C/strong\u003E; instead, it can survive in the acidic conditions of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe histology slide is taken from a gastric biopsy and shows tiny Helicobacter organisms (arrows) on the surface of the epithelium (Image). There is a chronic inflammatory infiltrate in the underlying lamina propria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Helicobacter pylori is a gram-negative, spiral-shaped bacterium that colonises the gastric mucosa","H. pylori infection can be diagnosed through multiple methods including histology, rapid urease test, urea breath test, and serology","H. pylori produces urease which allows it to survive in the acidic gastric environment"],"references":["Malfertheiner P, Camargo MC, El-Omar E, Liou JM, Peek R, Schulz C, Smith SI, Suerbaum S. Helicobacter pylori infection. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2023 Apr 20;9(1):19. doi: 10.1038/s41572-023-00431-8. PMID: 37081005; PMCID: PMC11558793.","Dunn BE, Cohen H, Blaser MJ. Helicobacter pylori. Clin Microbiol Rev. 1997 Oct;10(4):720-41. doi: 10.1128/CMR.10.4.720. PMID: 9336670; PMCID: PMC172942.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21212"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21212"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AYVZ4pq3zlT7cifwaqIzsLLwiTIs4K.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AYVZ4pq3zlT7cifwaqIzsLLwiTIs4K.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":397}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T10:31:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T10:32:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8135"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships"